Kerr's sign:

  • Shoulder tip pain caused by diaphrgmatic irritation with splenic laceration.
  • ⭐Congenital adrenal hyperplasia results from #autosomal-Recessive deficiency of 21-alpha hydroxylase enzyme. Deficiency diverts synthesis towards the androgenic pathway and decreases mineralocorticoid and glucocorticoid function.
  • ⭐increased testoterone -> virilization
  • ⭐Impaired aldosterone -> salt wasting.
  • ⭐females -> ambiguous genitalia
  • ⭐Males -> salt wasting crisis will be the presenting feature at < 10 days old.
  • Holmes-adie syndrome is associated with migraine.
    • There is partial or total loss of neurons of the ciliary ganglion. (and also loss of some spinal neurons)

Postpartum cardiomyopathy

  • Occurs from 1 month before to 5 months after delivery.
  • PPCM is diagnosed when no other cause is identified.
  • Risk factors:
    • Advanced maternal age
    • High parity, high gravidity, Twin pregnancy
    • Hypertension
    • Cocaine use
    • Poverty
      Source
  • Daily recurring fever or two fever spikes per day.
  • Arthralgia or arthritis - mild transient oligoarticular arthritis but can progress to severe arthritis.
  • Investigation: Leukocytosis, ⬆ESR, ⬆ CRP, ⬆ Ferritin, ⬆ hepatic aminotransferase.

Diabetic nephropathy

  1. Diffuse mesangial sclerosis <- diffuse ⭐increase of mesangial cells and matrix.
  2. Glomerular basement membrane thickening is the first to be seen.
    1. ⭐ACEI OR ARB is recommended for BP control - Good evidence for slowing of progression of CKD
    2. Target ⭐HBA1C of < 7 (subject to individual considerations)
  3. ⭐Use SGLT 2 inhibitors in addition to above measures in DM + DKD
    2. ⭐They decrease rate of progression of DKD - CREDENCE trial
    3. ⭐They reduce cardiovascular risk
  4. ⭐Spironolactone can be used because it reduces albuminuria but risk of hyperkalemia.
  • SGLT2 inhibitors are not appropriate for use in patients with type 1 diabetes and kidney disease.
  • KSS - kaerns sayre syndrome => CPEO at a young age (< 20) + pigmentary retinopathy.

Mechanisms of defence against intracellular pathogens


Cells involved in defence against intracellular pathogens:

  • CD8 cytotoxic cells.
  • Natural killer cells
  • Antibodies play little to no role.
  • CD4 helper cells 'help' by activating BOTH macrophages and CD8+ cells to do the killing.
    Cytokines:
  • Interferron gamma is vital in activating macrophages which have engulfed intracellular pathogens.

There are two types of HIV virus. ⭐HIV-1 is more virulent and causes most of the HIV infections, compared to HIV-2.Source-Wiki
⭐80-90% of all CD4 cells are killed due to infection within the first few weeks. Patients are still undiagnosed at this point.

Seroconversion can take a  ⭐few weeks to 3 months, during which time you may or may not have symptoms.

  • ⭐symmetrical polyarthritis
    ART quickly reduces viral load – by 90% in a few days. Viral load should then become ⭐undetectable within 1 to 3 months.
  • Nat: 10 to 33 days (so even NAT has a window period of upto 1 month)
  • ⭐Antibody test alone may not be sensitive enough within 6 weeks after exposure.
    Symptoms in this phase commonly ⭐involve the mucous membranes:
  • ⭐oral hairy leukoplakia
    Sometimes, a ⭐CD4 count < 50 is called "advanced HIV infection"
  • IgG is passed to the foetus via the placenta so ⭐presence of foetal IgG does not confirm infection.
    Low pre-antiretroviral therapy (ART) CD4 counts are associated with poor immune recovery following ART initiation. So early initiation of ART is crucial.
  • Effective ART results in sustained suppression of HIV RNA, improved cellular immunity (ie, CD4 count), and reduced HIV-immune activation (eg, proinflammatory cytokines, ⭐chronic inflammation, and T cell activation).
  • Life expectancy on ART is ⭐almost normal.
    There is a syndrome of peripheral fat loss with abdominal fat deposition associated with low HDL and high TGL and insulin resistance. This is called ⭐antiretroviral associated lipodystrophy

Sickle cell disease [[Haematology MCQ discussion#Q5 Sickle cell disease]]
  • If we use electron microscopy, we see that the immune complexes are dome shaped ⭐sub-epithelial deposits (aka "humps"). These are CHARACTERISTIC of PSGN. Subendothelial humps are also seen.
  • Renal biopsy in PSGN shows diffuse, florid, acute inflammation in the glomerulus (without necrosis but occasionally with cellular crescents) with ⭐neutrophils and deposition of IgG and complement

There is ⭐increased cellularity of the glomerular tufts, caused both by ⭐proliferation and swelling of endothelial and mesangial cells and by infiltrating neutrophils and monocytes.
Macroscopic:
On gross appearance, the kidneys may be enlarged up to 50%. Histopathologic changes include swelling of the glomerular tufts and infiltration with polymorphonucleocytes (see
Indications for Biopsy

  • Requirement for dialysis is unusual -> if so, may need biopsy.
  • If C3 is normal on presentation or doesn't rise after 6 - 8 weeks -> unusual -> may need biopsy.
    • i.e the normal picture is low C3 which rises back to normal 6-8 weeks
  • Progressive decline in renal function
  • Anuric renal failure
  • No latent period between strep infection and PSGN.
  • When no rise in ASOT titre.

[!INFO] CMT is a Slowly progressive peripheral ⭐motor + ⭐sensory neuropathy
Features are very similar to Friedrich's ataxia but CMT has no cerebellar signs and CMT probably presents at an older age.

  • CMT-1: "Demyelinating" Pain and temperature are usually not affected because they are carried by unmyelinated "C-Fibers". Type 1 is #autosomalDominant inherited. CMT 1 is the commonest form.
    • An unstable type of myelin is formed and repeated myelination and demyelination lead to ⭐thickened nerves.
  • Lower limbs more involved than upper limbs; frequent tripping and sprained ankles; steppage gait due to ⭐foot drop.

NK cells are lymphocytes but do not express antigen specific receptors like T or B cells.

  • MHC class I molecules are downregulated by a cell a in response to viral infections, other infections and stress. (and loss of MHC class I prevents inhibition of the NK cell)
  • Activator receptor binding molecules are expressed on cells with DNA damage, stress or infections.

Usually not caused by genetic inheritance: i.e sporadic.
Normally, only the paternal copy of the prader-willi gene containing region of chromosome 15 is expressed. This is called paternal imprinting. This paternal expression can be lost due to deletion, maternal uniparental disomy, or imprinting defect. Source

Standard error of the mean = the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample means = "A measure of how different the population mean is from the sample mean".

Standard error = Standard deviation / Square root of the sample size.
I.e higher the sample size, the lower the standard error.
